        "1.What is Linux?\n",
        "- Linux is an open-source, Unix-based operating system developed by Linus Torvalds in 1991. An operating system is system software that acts as an interface between the user and the computer hardware.\n",
        "- It manages hardware resources such as the CPU, memory, storage devices, and input/output devices while providing an environment for running applications.\n",
        "- Linux is known for its stability, security, performance, and flexibility. Since its source code is freely available, anyone can modify and distribute it under the GNU General Public License (GPL).\n",
        "- Linux is widely used in web servers, cloud computing, supercomputers, Android devices, embedded systems, and enterprise environments.\n",
        "- Features of Linux:\n",
        "   - Linux is free to use, and its source code can be viewed, modified, and distributed by anyone.\n",
        "   - Linux allows multiple users to access and use the same system simultaneously with separate accounts and permissions\n",
        "   - Linux can run multiple applications and processes at the same time without affecting system performance.\n",
        "   - Linux provides strong security through user authentication, file permissions, and access control mechanisms.\n",
        "\n",
        "2.What is the difference between Hard Link and Soft Link?\n",
        "  - HARD LINK creates another name for the same file. Both the original file and the hard link point to the same inode, meaning they share the same data on the disk.\n",
        "  - If the original file is deleted, the hard link still works because the data remains available until all hard links are removed.\n",
        "  - example:\n",
        "    \n",
        "          touch data.txt\n",
        "          echo \"Linux Assignment\" > data.txt\n",
        "          ln data.txt data_hardlink  \n",
        "\n",
        "          rm data.txt   #If you delete the original file\n",
        "          cat data_hardlink  #The hard link still contains the data\n",
        "\n",
        "  - A SOFT LINK (also called a Symbolic Link) is a special file that stores the path (location) of another file rather than its inode. It works like a shortcut in Windows.\n",
        "  - If the original file is deleted or moved, the soft link becomes broken because it can no longer find the original file.\n",
        "  - EXAMPLE:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "          touch data.txt\n",
        "          echo \"Linux Assignment\" > data.txt\n",
        "          ln -s data.txt data_link  \n",
        "\n",
        "          rm data.txt   #If you delete the original file\n",
        "          cat data_link  #If we run this command it will give error becuase soft link only stores the path of the original file.\n",
        "\n",
        "3.What is a Kernel in Linux?\n",
        "  - The Kernel is the core component of the Linux operating system. It acts as an intermediary between the hardware and software.\n",
        "  - An application needs access to hardware resources such as memory, CPU, storage, or input/output devices, the request is handled by the kernel.\n",
        "  - The kernel is loaded into memory during system startup and remains active until the system shuts down.\n",
        " - Functions of Kernel:<br>\n",
        "    a)<b> Process Management:</b>Creates, schedules, and terminates processes.<br>\n",
        "    b)<b> Memory Management:</b> Allocates and deallocates memory for running applications.<br>\n",
        "    c)<b> Device Management:</b> Communicates with hardware devices through device drivers.<br>\n",
        "    d) <b>File System Management:</b> Manages files, directories, and storage devices.<br>\n",
        "    e) <b>CPU Scheduling: </b>Determines which process gets CPU time.\n",
        "- Example:\n",
        "When you save a document, the application sends the request to the kernel. The kernel writes the data to the storage device using the appropriate device driver.   \n",
        "        \n",
        "4.How do you create a user account?\n",
        "  - User Account Steps are as follows:\n",
        "    ```bash\n",
        "       sudo useradd p1  # Create a user\n",
        "       sudo passwd p1   # Set a password\n",
        "       id p1            # Verify the user\n",
        "    ```\n",
    5.What is the grep command used for in Linux?\n",
        "  - The grep (Global Regular Expression Print) command is used to search for a specific word, string, or pattern in one or more files. It displays all lines that match the specified pattern.\n",
        "  - It is commonly used for searching log files, configuration files, and command outputs.\n",
        "  - Common Options:\n",
        "    - i → Ignore case sensitivity\n",
        "    - n → Show line numbers\n",
        "    - v → Display lines that do not match\n",
        "    - r → Search recursively\n",
        "  - Syntax:\n",
        "    - grep [options] pattern filename\n",
        "  - Example:\n",
        "    - grep \"error\" logfile.txt\n",
